h due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n459,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE FORMULA\"\"\",\"The \"\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE FORMULA\"\" is defined as \"\"Breakeven revenue = Number of units at BEP * Unit selling price.\"\" This formula calculates the revenue needed to cover all fixed and variable costs, ensuring that the business neither makes a profit nor incurs a loss at the breakeven point.\",6\n456,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN POINT (BEP)\"\"\",\"The breakeven point (BEP) is the level of sales at which total revenue equals total costs, resulting in zero profit. At BEP, the total contribution equals the fixed cost. The formula to calculate the BEP is given by dividing the total fixed cost by the unit contribution. In this case, the BEP is calculated as 340,000 divided by 40, which equals 8,500 units.\",6\n452,\"\"\"MARGIN OF SAFETY\"\"\",\"\"\"Margin of Safety\"\" is a financial metric that represents the difference between actual or projected sales and the breakeven sales volume. It measures the risk of a business falling below its breakeven point. The margin of safety can be expressed in units, dollars, or as a percentage, indicating the amount by which anticipated or existing activity exceeds (or falls short of) the breakeven point.\n\nFor example, in a quiz on calculating the margin of safety for Cummings Co., which manufactures a single product sold for $5, with annual sales revenue of $80,000, annual fixed costs of $25,000, and a contribution/sales ratio of 40%, the margin of safety is calculated as ((16,000 - 12,500) / 16,000) * 100% = 21.9%. This calculation demonstrates how the margin of safety can be applied in a real-world scenario to assess the financial health and risk of a business.\",4\n462,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE USING C/S RATIO\"\"\",\"\"\"Breakeven revenue = Fixed cost / C/S ratio\"\"\",2\n484,\"\"\"FIXED COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Fixed cost\"\" refers to business expenses that are not dependent on the level of goods or services produced by the business. These costs do not change with the level of production or sales volume and remain constant regardless of the business's output. Examples of fixed costs include rent, salaries, and insurance.\",2\n463,\"\"\"MARGIN OF SAFETY FORMULA\"\"\",\"The \"\"MARGIN OF SAFETY FORMULA\"\" is a financial metric used to determine the difference between budgeted sales and break-even sales. It can be expressed in two ways: \n\n1. As a ratio, calculated by subtracting break-even sales units from budgeted sales units and then dividing the result by budgeted sales units. The formula is: Margin of safety = (Budgeted sales units \u2013 break-even sales units) / Budgeted sales units.\n\n2. As a percentage, calculated by subtracting break-even sales from budgeted sales and then dividing the result by budgeted sales, multiplied by 100%. The formula is: Margin of safety = (Budgeted sales - Breakeven sales) / Budgeted sales * 100%.\n\nBoth expressions provide insight into how much sales can drop before the business reaches its break-even point, thus indicating the risk level associated with the current sales forecast.\",2\n499,\"\"\"COST-VOLUME-PROFIT (CVP) ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"Cost-Volume-Profit (CVP) Analysis is a method used by managers to understand the relationship between cost, volume, and profit in decision-making. This analysis assumes that the variable cost per unit and the selling price per unit remain constant over the full range of production. Additionally, CVP analysis ignores the impact of changes in inventory.\",1\n1410,\"\"\"MARGIN OF SAFETY PERCENTAGE\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the margin of safety percentage for Log Co\u2019s only product. The quiz provides sales price, direct materials, direct labour, variable production overhead, fixed production overhead, profit per unit, and sales commission, and asks for the margin of safety percentage.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n485,\"\"\"BREAKEVEN REVENUE FORMULA\"\"\",\"\"\"WEIGHTED AVERAGE C/S RATIO\"\"\",\"The breakeven r